            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_01">
                <pb n="1"/>
                <note type="letterhead">
                    <address>
                            <addrLine>ASYLUM HILL CONGREGATIONAL CHURCH</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>HARTFORD, CONN.</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>JOHN BROWNLEE VOORHEES, MINISTER</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>
                              <placeName key="854 Asylum Ave., Hartford, CT" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=41_46_12_N_72_41_43_W">854 ASYLUM AVE.</placeName>
                              </addrLine>
                            </address>
                </note>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1918-04-20">April 20, 1918.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Voorhees, Ralph Spencer Jr." cert="low"
                            from-iso="189-" to-iso="19--" role="Sargeant, Medical Department"
                            ref="https://doi.org/doi:10.7282/T3RB77D9">Ralph</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>

                <p> I am very sorry that I could not attend the meeting of the Alumni Council on
                        <date when="1918-04-13">April 13th</date>. These happen to be very busy days
                    with me, as I plan to start shortly for overseas service in connection with the
                        <name type="org">Y.M.C.A.</name>, my Church having granted me eight months
                    leave of absence. </p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very truly yours,</salute><lb/>
                    <handShift medium="black-ink"/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                            role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">John
                            Brownlee Voorhees</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_02">
                <pb n="2"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1918-04-25">April 25, 1918.</date><lb/>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                          <addrLine>
                            <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919" role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr.
                                J. B. Voorhees,</persName>
                          </addrLine>
                          <addrLine>
                            <name type="org">Asylum Hill Congregational Church,</name>
                          </addrLine>
                          <addrLine><placeName key="854 Asylum Ave., Hartford, CT" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=41_46_12_N_72_41_43_W"> 854 Asylum Ave.<lb/> Hartford, Conn.</placeName></addrLine>
                        </address>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                            role="Minister, Asylum Hill Congregational Church, and Secretary, YMCA" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr.
                            Voorhees</persName>: </salute>
                </opener>
                <p> I understand that you will leavershortly for overseas service with the Y.M.C.A.
                    If you will send me your address, I shall be pleased to include you in the list
                    of those who receive the benefits of our War Service Bureau. </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute> Wishing you success in this most interesting field of work, I am<lb/>
                        Sincerely yours, </salute><lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >Director. <lb/>ERS/H</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_03">
                <pb n="3"/>

                <note type="letterhead">
                    <address>
                          <addrLine>ASYLUM HILL CONGREGATIONAL CHURCH</addrLine>
                          <addrLine>HARTFORD, CONN.</addrLine>
                          <addrLine>JOHN BROWNLEE VOORHEES, MINISTER</addrLine>
                          <addrLine>
                            <placeName key="854 Asylum Ave., Hartford, CT" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=41_46_12_N_72_41_43_W">854 ASYLUM AVE.</placeName>
                            </addrLine>
                          </address>
                </note>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1918-05-02">May 2, 1918.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                          <addrLine>
                            <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948" role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378">Mr. Earl Reed
                            Silvers,</persName>
                          </addrLine>
                          <addrLine>
                            <placeName key="Rutgers College, New Brunswick, NJ" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_29_55_N_74_26_54_W">New Brunswick, N. J.</placeName>
                          </addrLine>
                        </address>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >Mr. Silvers</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I leave this week for eight months Y.M.C.A. service overseas. My address will be
                    American Y.M.C.A., <placeName key="12 rue d'Aguesseau, Paris, France"
                        ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=48_52_13_N_2_19_10_E"
                        >12 Rue d'Aggesseau, Paris, France</placeName>. I shall certainly appreciate
                    being included in the benefits of the Rutgers War Service Bureau. News from
                    college will look good across the seas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially ever,</salute><lb/>
                    <signed><persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                            role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">John
                            Brownlee Voorhees</persName></signed>
                </closer>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_04">
                <pb n="4"/>
                <head>
                    <stamp>GIFT OF THE<lb/> AMERICAN PEOPLE<lb/> THROUGH THE<lb/> AMERICAN RED
                        CROSS<lb/> TO THOSE IN SERVICE</stamp>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <address>
                          <addrLine>
                            <placeName key="U.S.A. Base Hospital No. 20, Châtel-Guyon, France" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=45.9233_N_3.065_E">U.S.A. Base Hospital No. 20</placeName>
                          </addrLine>
                          <addrLine>Central France.</addrLine>
                        </address>
                    <dateline><date when="1918-09-18">Sept 18, 1918</date></dateline>
                    <salute>My Dear <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >Silvers</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>This is just to thank you for the War Service letters. I came over last May to
                    work under the Y.M.C.A.; but the <seg xml:id="fn1">Boche</seg>
                    <note resp="#FG" target="#fn1" type="gloss">
                        <ref
                            target="http://www.oed.com.proxy.libraries.rutgers.edu/view/Entry/20870"
                            > Boche, n. and adj. OED Online. June 2017. Oxford University
                            Press.</ref>
                        <p>A derogatory term for a German. Usually plural.</p>
                    </note> considered my activities too dangerous, and decided to shoot up <seg
                        xml:id="fn4">the town</seg><note resp="#FG" type="annotation" target="#fn4">
                        <p>Voorhees was on duty with the 26th Division northwest of Toul, France,
                            when the hut was bombarded on June 19th. Voorhees was with C.W. Peel, of
                            Fitchburg, MA.</p>
                        <ref target="https://books.google.com/books?id=cbvsmqOcR1wC">The
                            Congregationalist and Advance, vol. 104</ref>
                    </note> where my hut was located. They demolished the hut and incidentally sent
                    a chunk of high explosive through my right leg. The result has been that I have
                    spent the summer of 1918 on the flat of my back with the aforesaid leg hung up
                    in a complicated apparatus which has kept my right toe pointing at the North
                    star for three months.</p>
                <p><seg xml:id="fn2">But it is not as bad as it sounds</seg>, <note resp="#FG"
                        type="annotation" target="#fn2">
                        <quote>cheerful, confident spirit</quote>
                        <ref target="https://doi.org/doi:10.7282/T34M97D7">Silvers, Earl Reed.
                            Obituaries and Memorials, p. 54.</ref>
                    </note> and on the whole it has not been a bad summer. Uncle Sam's Army
                    Hospitals are great institutions, and the best that medical science and surgical
                    skill can offer is yours to command. Also it is cheap. I have saved at least
                    $10000. in surgeon's fees by coming over to <pb n="5"/> to France to be shot up.
                    So you see I am considerably ahead of the game.</p>
                <p>Some day soon or late <seg xml:id="fn3">I expect to get back to the
                        States</seg><note resp="#FG" type="annotation" target="#fn3">
                        <quote>arrived in New York Christmas eve</quote>
                        <ref target="https://books.google.com/books?id=XWQzAQAAMAAJ">Association
                            Men. v. 44. International Committee of the Associations, 1918, p.
                            456.</ref>
                    </note>, and with a right leg adequate at last to the ancient and honorable game
                    of golf. I am afraid, however, I have lost my drive.</p>
                <p>It begins to look as if America had sent a real army overseas. Well, it has been
                    on of the big privileges of my life to have some association with it, short as
                    it was. It has been worth coming over, despite my contact with a ten inch
                    shell.</p>
                <p>Keep on with the letters. I shall be in the hospital some time yet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours ever</salute><lb/>
                    <signed><persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                            role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">John
                            Brownlee Voorhees</persName> '96</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>LSS <unclear>files</unclear><lb/>1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> Lt 314<hi
                            rend="superscript">th</hi> Engrs.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_05">
                <pb n="6"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline><date when="1918-10-24">October 24, <lb/> 1 9 18</date></dateline>
                    <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919" role="Minister"
                        ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr. John B.
                        Voorhees</persName>, <lb/>
                    <placeName key="U.S.A. Base Hospital No. 20, Châtel-Guyon, France"
                        ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=45.9233_N_3.065_E"
                        >Base Hospital #20 <lb/> American E.F.</placeName>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                            role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr.
                            Voorhees</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your letter of September 18 was very welcome. Here at the college we have been
                    worrying about you and our only word has come indirectly. We are glad to know
                    that your injured limb is in the process of healing and we trust that you will
                    not have to spend very much more time in the hospital.</p>
                <p>There must be a lot of satisfaction to you in the thought that you have served so
                    bravely and courageously in the big cause in which you are enlisted.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed><persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >ERS/G</persName></signed>
                </closer>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_06">
                <pb n="8"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline><date when="1919-01-13">January 13, 1919</date></dateline>
                    <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956" role="Spouse"
                        ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011">Mrs. J. Brownlee
                        Voorhees</persName>,<lb/>
                    <placeName key="854 Asylum Ave., Hartford, CT"
                        ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=41_46_12_N_72_41_43_W"
                        >854 Asylum Ave. <lb/> Hartford, Conn.</placeName>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                            role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011">Mrs.
                            Voorhees</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p> It is with very great regret that we have heard of the death of your husband,
                        <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919"
                        role="Minister" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr. J.
                        Brownlee Voorhees</persName>. May I express to you my deepest sympathy, both
                    personally, and as Director of the War Service Bureau. Dr. Voorhees has sent us
                    several letters from France and his continued optimism in the face of many
                    difficulties has been a source of much inspiration for us. His loss is a big one
                    and his place will be hard to fill, I know. </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                </closer>
            </div>

            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_07">
                <pb n="9"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1919-02-03">February 3, 1919</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <persName key="Berg, Irving Husted" role="Minister" from="1878" to="1941"
                        ref="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23135271">Rev. Irving H. Berg</persName>,<lb/>
                    <placeName key="2611 Sedgwick Ave, New York, NY"
                        ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_52_8_N_73_54_19_W"
                        >2611 Sedgewick Avenue,<lb/> New York, N.Y.</placeName>
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Berg;-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>We are very anxious to secure for the Rutgers Alumni Quarterly and for our
                    college records, a photograph of the <persName key="Voorhees, John Brownlee"
                        from="1875" to="1919" role="Minister"
                        ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Rev. J. Brownlee
                        Voorhees</persName>. <persName key="Demarest, William Henry Steele"
                        role="President, Rutgers College" from="1863" to="1956"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/28550683">Dr. Demarest</persName> has suggested
                    that possibly you may have one on hand. If you have, I shall be very grateful if
                    you will permit us to use for the making of a zinc cut. It will only take a few
                    days, and the picture will not be harmed.</p>
                <p>I hesitate to write <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                        role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011">Mrs.
                        Voorhees</persName> at this time. Will you please advise us, if you have not
                    a picture!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Thanking you,<lb/> I am<lb/> Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                </closer>
            </div>

