                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>
                          <persName key="Berg, Irving Husted" role="Minister" from="1878" to="1941" ref="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23135271">Rev. Irving H. Berg,</persName>
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Fort Washington Collegiate Church,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>
                          <placeName key="729 West 181st Street, New York, NY 10033" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_51_3_N_73_56_23_W">729 West 181st St.</placeName>,
                      </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>New York City.</addrLine>
                      </address>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Berg, Irving Husted" role="Minister" from="1878"
                            to="1941" ref="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23135271">Dr.
                        Berg</persName>:--</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you very such for your letter of February 4th.</p>
                <p>I appreciate your writing to <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880"
                        to="1956" role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011"
                        >Mrs. Voorhees</persName>, and hope that the picture of <persName
                        key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919" role="Minister"
                        ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Dr. Voorhees</persName>
                    will reach us soon. I shall advise you if it does not come.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >ERS/W </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
