                <note type="letterhead">
                    <address>
                <addrLine>THE PARSONAGE</addrLine>
                <addrLine><placeName key="854 Asylum Ave., Hartford, CT" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=41_46_12_N_72_41_43_W">854 ASYLUM AVENUE</placeName></addrLine>
                <addrLine>HARTFORD, CONN</addrLine>
              </address>
                </note>
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >Silvers</persName>,</salute>
                </opener>

                <p><persName key="Berg, Irving Husted" role="Minister" from="1878" to="1941"
                        ref="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23135271">Dr. Berg</persName> sent me your
                        <unclear quantity="2" unit="words"/> request for a picture of my husband.
                    some had been ordered and they have just arrived after all these weeks. I am
                    sending <unclear quantity="1" unit="words">one</unclear> to you under <unclear
                        quantity="2" unit="words">separate cover</unclear>. I understand you will
                        <pb n="13"/> return it. </p>
                <p>There was certainly no more loyal son of Rutgers than <persName
                        key="Voorhees, John Brownlee" from="1875" to="1919" role="Minister"
                        ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130098973">Mr. Voorhees</persName>.
                    The college was always close to his <unclear>heart</unclear>. </p>
                <p>I deeply appreciate your sympathy at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed><persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                            role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011"
                            >Juliana Deyo Voorhees</persName></signed>
                    <dateline><date when="1919-03-11" cert="medium">march
                                <unclear>eleventh</unclear></date></dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_11">
                <pb n="14"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline><date when="1919-03-17">March 17th, 1919.</date></dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mrs. Julian D. Voorhees,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>854 Aslylum Avenue,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Hartford, Conn.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                            role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011">Mrs.
                            Voorhees</persName>;-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for the photograph of Doctor Voorhees, which arrived this morning.</p>
                <p>We shall take excellent care of it and return it to you within the next two
                    weeks.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                </closer>
            </div>
            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_12">
                <pb n="15"/>
                <opener>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine><placeName key="205 Tuttle Ave, Spring Lake, NJ" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_9_30_N_74_1_33_W">205 Tuttle Ave</placeName></addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Spring Lake</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>NJ.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948"
                            role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"
                            >Mr. Silvers</persName>.</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I understood that my husband's picture would be returned to me. perhaps it has
                    been sent to Hartford since I left there. If not would you have it sent here.
                    also I would <pb n="16"/> like a copy of the <title>Alumni Quarterly</title>
                    that his picture was in.</p>
                <p>Thanking you for any <unclear>trouble</unclear> this may cause you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am most sincerely yours</salute>
                    <signed><persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                            role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011"
                            >Juliana Deyo Voorhees</persName> (Mrs. J. B).</signed>
                    <date when="1919-07-10">July 10</date> - </closer>
            </div>
            <div type="letter" decls="#voorheesjb_13">
                <pb n="18"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline><date when="1919-07-14">July 14th, 1919</date>.</dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine><persName>Mrs. J. B. Voorhees</persName>,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine><placeName key="205 Tuttle Ave, Spring Lake, NJ" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_9_30_N_74_1_33_W">205 Tuttle Ave.</placeName>,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Spring Lake, N. J.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="Voorhees, Juliana Deyo" from="1880" to="1956"
                            role="Spouse" ref="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/130099011">Mrs.
                            Voorhees</persName>:-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Dr. Voorhees' picture was returned to Hartford at least six weeks ago. I hope
                    that it has not been lost.</p>
                <p>Under separate cover I am sending you copies of the Quarterly in which are items
                    concerning him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
